\subsection{Conditional estimands at representative profiles}

To illustrate heterogeneity, we evaluate conditional effects at four
covariate profiles that differ across all variables. Each profile is
constructed on the original data scale using sample quantiles for
continuous covariates and observed factor levels for categorical ones.
The raw profiles are then standardized using the training-sample
centering and scaling constants and mapped through the same
\code{model.matrix()} encoding used in the fit so that factor
combinations remain valid. The profile table is shown below; the
intermediate design-matrix construction is hidden because it is not part
of the package-facing workflow.

<<app_lalonde_xnew-code, echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE, eval=TRUE>>=
app_lalonde_numeric_quantile <- function(x, prob = 0.50) {
  as.numeric(stats::quantile(x, probs = prob, na.rm = TRUE, names = FALSE))
}

app_lalonde_profile_raw <- data.frame(
  profile = c("Profile 1", "Profile 2", "Profile 3", "Profile 4"),
  age = c(
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$age, 0.25),
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$age, 0.50),
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$age, 0.75),
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$age, 0.90)
  ),
  educ = c(
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$educ, 0.25),
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$educ, 0.50),
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$educ, 0.75),
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$educ, 0.90)
  ),
  race = factor(
    c("black", "hispan", "white", "black"),
    levels = levels(app_lalonde_covars$race)
  ),
  married = factor(
    c("no", "no", "yes", "yes"),
    levels = levels(app_lalonde_covars$married)
  ),
  nodegree = factor(
    c("yes", "no", "no", "yes"),
    levels = levels(app_lalonde_covars$nodegree)
  ),
  re74 = c(
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$re74, 0.20),
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$re74, 0.40),
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$re74, 0.60),
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$re74, 0.80)
  ),
  re75 = c(
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$re75, 0.20),
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$re75, 0.40),
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$re75, 0.60),
    app_lalonde_numeric_quantile(app_lalonde_covars$re75, 0.80)
  ),
  row.names = c("p1", "p2", "p3", "p4"),
  check.names = FALSE
)

app_lalonde_profile_model <- within(app_lalonde_profile_raw, {
  age_z <- (age - app_lalonde_scale_center[["age"]]) /
    app_lalonde_scale_scale[["age"]]
  educ_z <- (educ - app_lalonde_scale_center[["educ"]]) /
    app_lalonde_scale_scale[["educ"]]
  re74_z <- (re74 - app_lalonde_scale_center[["re74"]]) /
    app_lalonde_scale_scale[["re74"]]
  re75_z <- (re75 - app_lalonde_scale_center[["re75"]]) /
    app_lalonde_scale_scale[["re75"]]
})

app_lalonde_xnew <- stats::model.matrix(
  app_lalonde_x_formula,
  data = app_lalonde_profile_model
)[, -1, drop = FALSE]
app_lalonde_xnew <- app_lalonde_xnew[, colnames(app_lalonde_X), drop = FALSE]
@

<<app_lalonde_xnew-results, echo=FALSE, eval=TRUE, results='asis'>>=
app_lalonde_profile_display <- app_lalonde_profile_raw[
  ,
  c("profile", "age", "educ", "race", "married", "nodegree", "re74", "re75"),
  drop = FALSE
]
rownames(app_lalonde_profile_display) <- NULL
kableExtra::kbl(
  app_lalonde_profile_display,
  format = "latex",
  booktabs = TRUE,
  caption = "Representative Lalonde participant profiles used for conditional causal contrasts",
  row.names = FALSE
) |>
  kableExtra::kable_styling(
    latex_options = c("HOLD_position", "scale_down"),
    font_size = 8
  )
@

<<app_lalonde_cate-call, echo=TRUE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE, results='hide', eval=TRUE>>=
app_lalonde_cate_fit <- cate(
  app_lalonde_fit,
  newdata = app_lalonde_xnew,
  type = "mean",
  interval = "credible",
  show_progress = FALSE
)
@

Figure~\ref{fig:app_lalonde_cate_plot} displays the mean-based CATE
estimates across the four representative profiles, produced by the
package \code{plot()} method.

<<app_lalonde_cate_plot, echo=TRUE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE, eval=TRUE, out.width='0.85\\linewidth', fig.pos='H', fig.cap='Mean-based CATE estimates for Lalonde earnings at the four representative profiles with pointwise credible intervals.'>>=
plot(app_lalonde_cate_fit)
@

<<app_lalonde_cqte-call, echo=TRUE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE, results='hide', eval=TRUE>>=
app_lalonde_cqte_fit <- cqte(
  app_lalonde_fit,
  probs = app_lalonde_taus,
  newdata = app_lalonde_xnew,
  interval = "credible",
  show_progress = FALSE
)
@

Table~\ref{tab:app_lalonde_cqte_table} reports CQTE summaries at the
four representative profiles on the same quantile grid used in the
standardized QTE analysis.

<<app_lalonde_cqte-results, echo=FALSE, eval=TRUE, results='asis'>>=
app_lalonde_cqte_table <- as.data.frame(app_lalonde_cqte_fit$qte$fit)
if ("id" %in% names(app_lalonde_cqte_table)) {
  app_lalonde_cqte_table$profile <- paste0("Profile ", app_lalonde_cqte_table$id)
}

app_lalonde_cqte_show <- app_lalonde_cqte_table[
  ,
  intersect(c("profile", "id", "index", "estimate", "lower", "upper"), names(app_lalonde_cqte_table)),
  drop = FALSE
]

app_lalonde_cqte_num_cols <- intersect(c("index", "estimate", "lower", "upper"), names(app_lalonde_cqte_show))
app_lalonde_cqte_show[, app_lalonde_cqte_num_cols] <- lapply(
  app_lalonde_cqte_show[, app_lalonde_cqte_num_cols, drop = FALSE],
  round,
  digits = 3
)

kableExtra::kbl(
  app_lalonde_cqte_show,
  format = "latex",
  booktabs = TRUE,
  caption = "Conditional QTE estimates at representative Lalonde participant profiles.\\label{tab:app_lalonde_cqte_table}"
) |>
  kableExtra::kable_styling(
    latex_options = c("hold_position", "scale_down"),
    font_size = 8
  )
@

\subsection{Results and interpretation}

A key advantage of the spliced model is direct posterior inference on
the tail index $\xi_a$ by arm. Larger $\xi_a$ indicates a heavier upper
tail and greater propensity for extreme earnings realizations in the
corresponding arm. Table~\ref{tab:app_lalonde_tail_params} and
Table~\ref{tab:app_lalonde_tail_shape} summarize these posterior
parameter estimates.

\Sexpr{if (isTRUE(app_lalonde_xi_lt_one)) "Because both posterior arm-specific tail-shape means satisfy $\\\\hat\\\\xi_a < 1$, the corresponding arm-specific means exist; therefore the reported ATE and CATE summaries are well-defined in this analysis." else "At least one posterior arm-specific tail-shape mean is not below one, so mean-based summaries should be interpreted with additional caution."}

Taken together, the standardized and profile-specific summaries separate
two distinct questions: how the program shifts the overall earnings
distribution after averaging over the empirical covariate mix, and how
that shift changes across substantively different participant profiles.
The tail-shape summaries then add an explicitly extremal comparison by
showing how much posterior mass each arm assigns to heavier or lighter
upper-tail behavior.


\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\pkg{CausalMixGPD} combines flexible bulk density estimation, optional
EVT-based tail extrapolation, predictor-dependent clustering, and
distributional causal inference in one workflow. The same fitted model
supports posterior summaries for densities, survival curves, means,
restricted means, quantiles, and treatment contrasts, which avoids the
fragmented analysis pipelines often required when heavy tails and
distributional effects matter simultaneously.

The package is broader than the spliced examples emphasized here. Users
can work with bulk-only or spliced models, multiple kernel families on
the real line or positive support, SB or CRP backends, and clustering or
causal wrappers built on the same predictive machinery. That shared
infrastructure makes it easier to move from exploratory subgroup
analysis to tail-focused prediction and causal reporting without
changing the underlying modeling language.

The first practical limitation is computation. Mixture models with
covariate dependence, optional tail components, and arm-specific causal
fits are MCMC-intensive, and the cost increases further when users run
sensitivity analyses, longer chains, or richer predictor sets.

The second limitation is model tuning. A spliced analysis inherits
choices from both the DPM and peaks-over-threshold components, including
kernel family, truncation level, threshold specification, and the number
of exceedances available for tail learning. When overlap is weak or
exceedances are sparse, posterior uncertainty can be substantial, and
for clustering the posterior similarity matrix is often more reliable
than any single partition summary.

The third limitation is scope. The current causal implementation is
restricted to binary treatments and continuous outcomes under standard
consistency, ignorability, and overlap assumptions. Propensity-score
augmentation can improve adjustment in observational studies, but it is
not a substitute for design, overlap diagnostics, or sensitivity
analysis for unmeasured confounding.




